<div id="review_2621803876" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2621803876" />
    <a title="Brinley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8725179-brinley"><img alt="Brinley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556813238p2/8725179.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2621803876?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brinley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brinley" href="/user/show/8725179-brinley">Brinley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8725179-brinley?shelf=prisons">prisons</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2621803876" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8027937414426403670">In the introduction of this book, we learn how the complexities of Schenwar’s relationship to her sister correlate to the complexities of her thoughts on the validity of prisons. Kayla* (whose name was changed) has gone through a revolving door of being entered into prison, released, then re-entered again, and it takes a toll on their family. At the beginning of the book, Maya’s initial reaction to one of her recent arrests is one of gratitude: at least in jail she won’t be able to use drugs (or</span>
  <span id="freeText8027937414426403670" style="display:none">In the introduction of this book, we learn how the complexities of Schenwar’s relationship to her sister correlate to the complexities of her thoughts on the validity of prisons. Kayla* (whose name was changed) has gone through a revolving door of being entered into prison, released, then re-entered again, and it takes a toll on their family. At the beginning of the book, Maya’s initial reaction to one of her recent arrests is one of gratitude: at least in jail she won’t be able to use drugs (or hopefully not, at least). <br /><br />But the more you look into what being in jail is like, not only for Kayla, but for her family and friends, the more the question begins apparent: why do we believe that erasing someone from society is a valid response to harm? Schenwar doesn’t only focus on Kayla, though: she weaves her story with the stories of countless other inmates, families of inmates, activists, and abolition advocates to show how her story, while unique, reveals something that isn’t: prison isn’t working for anyone, whether you are the victim or perpetrator of a crime, or related to someone experiencing harm. Hardly any accomplishments or developments are made once you’re incarcerated; and being released doesn’t prepare you for any of the obstacles you will face once you reintegrate into society. <br /><br />Locked Down, Locked Out is not only about talking about what’s wrong with prisons and our ideas that surround them, Schenwar also makes a strong case for why writing letters to prisoners can be a radical act, outlines the importance of bringing restorative/ transformative justice circles into schools, and looks at different practices that hope to decarcerate our growing jail and prison population. Beyond all this, she questions our framework for what we consider a crime, why we feel like calling the police and involving the criminal justice system is a valid response to that (like when she files a police report over a theft and notes: “In fact, the process I bought into provided no support for me, beyond the false, momentary sense of security that came from filing a report. It was geared toward catching and punishing a person—or a bunch of people—rather than addressing the impact of my loss, or the causes of the “epidemic” in the first place. It’s just one component of a system obsessed not with solving problems or aiding victims, but with “crime”’. ), and why we prioritize some crimes more than others (for example, interpersonal violence is criminalized, but nuclear destruction is excused). What I liked most about this book is that she isn’t afraid to admit her hesitations or hold ups about abolition, instead choosing to write through them to at least plants seeds for further contemplation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8027937414426403670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


