<div id="review_1601937168" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1601937168" />
    <a title="Margaret Klein" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20767702-margaret-klein"><img alt="Margaret Klein" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408981340p2/20767702.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1601937168?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Margaret Klein" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Margaret Klein" href="/user/show/20767702-margaret-klein">Margaret Klein</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20767702-margaret-klein?shelf=2016">2016</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1601937168" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer705494899458644773">This book is an important read. It is a masterful balance between personal anecdote, real statistics and interviews with people who work tirelessly to improve our national approach to prison. It is not just a book about prison reform, although it talks about that too.<br/><br/>Maya&apos;s own sister has been in and out of prison and this book tracks their own personal story. How prison isolates, tears apart families and communities. Leads to recidivism.<br/><br/>The statistics are horrifying. 2.3 million locked up in th</span>
  <span id="freeText705494899458644773" style="display:none">This book is an important read. It is a masterful balance between personal anecdote, real statistics and interviews with people who work tirelessly to improve our national approach to prison. It is not just a book about prison reform, although it talks about that too.<br /><br />Maya's own sister has been in and out of prison and this book tracks their own personal story. How prison isolates, tears apart families and communities. Leads to recidivism.<br /><br />The statistics are horrifying. 2.3 million locked up in this country. Only 3% are competent reading. Disproportionate percentage of people of color. Too many who return within 3 years. 95% have less opportunities once released. <br /><br />It is a quick read but the topic is not easy. The stories stick with you. The problems are real. And big. The book synthesizes many of the issues around the prison industrial complex. And the school to prison pipeline. Best reading I have done on restorative justice and transformational justice with real examples of programs, including in the Chicago Public Schools that are working, at least in small groups. <br /><br />If you work for with prisoners, in the prison system, the school system, the legal system, the justice system, this book is for you. If you work as a community organizer, rabbi, minister, chaplain, prison guard, attorney, school administrator, teacher or in the police this book is for you.<br /><br />I look forward to hosting T'ruah's book discussion on this book.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="705494899458644773" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
