<span id="freeTextContainer15444245715695672278">“Conjugal visits” are in fact banned almost everywhere and for almost all prisoners. Four states (California, New York, New Mexico, and Washington) allow a limited number of “extended family visits”: time that can be spent in a more private setting, with either a legal spouse or other family members. (A few prisons in an additional four states allow overnight visits with children or grandchildren.) Though restrictions vary among different states and prisons, these choice visits are most often av</span>
  <span id="freeText15444245715695672278" style="display:none">“Conjugal visits” are in fact banned almost everywhere and for almost all prisoners. Four states (California, New York, New Mexico, and Washington) allow a limited number of “extended family visits”: time that can be spent in a more private setting, with either a legal spouse or other family members. (A few prisons in an additional four states allow overnight visits with children or grandchildren.) Though restrictions vary among different states and prisons, these choice visits are most often available to minimum- to medium-security prisoners who are STD-free and HIV-free, with no disciplinary markups while in prison. So where did Peter from Office Space get the idea that anonymous women might be magically carted in to satisfy prisoners’ “conjugal” needs?<br /><br />In a truly free world-a world of freed of prison in its every incarceration-all structures related to justice would look different. The maintenance of safety wouldn't translate into brutal policing, surveillance, punishment, in-school suspension, imprisonment, isolation, chained birth, torn-up families, shattered communities. <br /><br />Whenever we cage people, we are in reality fueling &amp; participating in the same spirit we claim to renounce. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15444245715695672278" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


